The Warm Obsidian Clock is a heat-responsive artifact in the Wizard's Keep's sealed northern corridor, associated with the Keep's chronometric and threshold-control systems.
The artifact's defining characteristic is its warming cycle: the obsidian surface heats on a repeating interval that matches no current lock-cycle schedule in the Keep's operating protocols.
The corridor where the Clock sits terminates at a blank wall with a circular groove — evidence of a removed or disabled mechanism that the Clock appears to be tracking or triggering.
Watcher-Sergeant Hask was the first officer to formally record the Clock's warming cycle, noting that it repeated on a consistent interval that did not correspond to any scheduled operation.
The Clock's warming interval correlates with timing that predates the Keep's current governance period, suggesting it is responding to a mechanism or schedule established during an earlier era of operation.
The Obsidian Interruption — the period when the deep-access corridor's mechanism was decommissioned — is associated with the Triple-Ledger Gap, suggesting the Clock was part of the same system whose records were selectively destroyed.
The Keep's Sanctum Continuity Office argues that the Clock's warming is a residual thermal signature from the decommissioning process, without ongoing operational significance.
The Reformist Adept Circle argues that the Clock's consistent interval proves something is still operating in the sealed space — either a mechanism that was not fully decommissioned or something that established itself after the decommissioning.
The obsidian material is notable: obsidian from the Keep's sealed corridor does not match any local quarry source, bearing the same nonlocal machining marks characteristic of items from the Obsidian Branch period.
The Keep's inquisitors have not formally investigated the Clock's warming cycle, classifying it as a "resolved maintenance anomaly" in official documentation — a classification disputed by several rank-and-file guard personnel.
The Clock is physically inaccessible without authorization from both the Keeper of the Sanctum and a senior inquisitor simultaneously.

